        {
            "author_association": "NONE",
            "body": "Right, I did add an `ftdetect/ansible.lua` with the following:\n\n```lua\n  vim.filetype.add({\n    pattern = {\n      [\".*/defaults/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/host_vars/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/group_vars/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/group_vars/.*/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/playbook.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/playbooks/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/roles/.*/tasks/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/roles/.*/handlers/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/tasks/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n      [\".*/molecule/.*%.ya?ml\"] = \"yaml.ansible\",\n    },\n  })\n```\nWorking with an Ansible project and opening files matching these expressions work (verified with `:set filetype?`).\n\nHowever, indeed, `:checkhealth` keeps crying wolf about it; I would expect `:checkhealth` to do something like: \"hey, this thing wants some `yaml.ansible` filetype, let me see if that's registered; if not I warn, if it is, I don't\".",
